                        textEn: 'After the dust of battles settled across the Arabian Peninsula, history witnessed the birth of a global power that would drastically redraw the map of the world. Entering the era of the Umayyad Caliphate, the frontiers of civilization were redefined. Under the command of great caliphs like Al-Walid ibn Abd al-Malik, the thundering hooves of the Islamic cavalry were unstoppable — echoing from the expanses of West Asia, sweeping across the shores of North Africa, and piercing the very heart of Europe in Spain. Yet, the Umayyad Caliphate was far from a mere machine of conquest. Behind the clash of swords and the howling desert winds, a masterpiece of civilization was being erected upon formidable foundations. State administration and governance were meticulously structured, the Arabic language was decreed as the unifying tongue, and urban infrastructure expanded rapidly to connect global arteries. On the horizon of Damascus, the monumental crowns of architecture, such as the Great Mosque, began to rise against the sky. This structure was not merely a place of prostration, but a visual proclamation that Islam had transformed from a desert entity into a colossal empire shaping world civilization.',
