                        textEn: 'Entering the mid-8th century, the pages of history turned their course from Damascus to the banks of the Tigris River. It was there that the Abbasid Caliphate founded Baghdad, a magnificent round city destined to become the beating heart of world civilization. Under the illustrious leadership of its fifth caliph, Harun Al-Rashid — a ruler of profound justice and authority — the empire expanded not only its territorial borders but the very boundaries of the human mind. Baghdad blossomed into a global metropolis, a crossroads for merchant caravans from the farthest east to the west, weaving an economic prosperity without precedent. Yet, the greatest legacy of the Abbasids lay not in swords or gold, but in the pen. Through the grand institution of the House of Wisdom (Baitul Hikmah), this civilization began to gather, translate, and perfect the intellectual masterpieces of ancient Greece, Persia, and India, laying the foundations for an era of enlightenment that would illuminate the world for centuries, before the dark clouds from the East prepared to eclipse this glory in 1258.',
