                        textId: 'Pada tahun 1258, langit Baghdad tertutup abu hitam. Gelombang invasi bangsa Mongol membumihanguskan jantung peradaban ini, melemparkan jutaan manuskrip berharga ke Sungai Tigris hingga airnya menghitam oleh tinta. Kekhalifahan Abbasiyah secara politik telah runtuh, namun narasi sejarah menolak untuk berhenti di sana. Di tengah puing-puing kehancuran, percikan api peradaban Islam justru tertiup angin dan menyebar ke seluruh penjuru mata angin. Di ufuk barat dan tengah, sisa-sisa kekuatan memicu kebangkitan tiga kekaisaran mesiu raksasa: Kesultanan Utsmaniyah di Turki, Kekaisaran Safawiyah di Persia, dan Mughal di India — yang masing-masing merajut kembali kejayaan politik dan budaya Islam. Sementara itu, gelombang ekspansi yang jauh lebih sunyi namun mendalam terjadi ke arah Timur. Melalui jalur sutra maritim, para pedagang dan ulama membawa cahaya Islam berlayar menuju Asia Selatan hingga meresap ke dalam kebudayaan pesisir Nusantara. Runtuhnya satu imperium ternyata menjadi katalis bagi lahirnya dunia Islam yang jauh lebih majemuk, membuktikan bahwa nilai-nilai keagamaan, ilmu pengetahuan, dan tradisi kultural tidak dapat dihancurkan oleh pedang penakluk mana pun.',
                        textEn: 'In 1258, the skies over Baghdad were blotted out by black ash. The wave of the Mongol invasion laid waste to the heart of this civilization, casting millions of priceless manuscripts into the Tigris River until its waters ran black with ink. The Abbasid Caliphate had politically collapsed, yet the historical narrative refused to end there. Amidst the ruins of destruction, the sparks of Islamic civilization were caught by the wind, scattering across every point of the compass. In the west and central horizons, the remnants of power ignited the rise of three colossal gunpowder empires: the Ottoman Sultanate in Turkey, the Safavid Empire in Persia, and the Mughal Empire in India — each weaving anew the political and cultural glory of Islam. Meanwhile, a much quieter yet profoundly deep wave of expansion flowed Eastward. Navigating the maritime silk roads, merchants and scholars carried the light of Islam across the seas to South Asia, permeating the coastal cultures of the Nusantara archipelago. The fall of one empire ultimately acted as the catalyst for the birth of a vastly more pluralistic Islamic world, proving that religious values, science, and cultural traditions cannot be extinguished by any conqueror\'s sword.',
