                        textEn: 'At the dawn of the 16th century, from the vortex of conflict in the Middle East, the Safavid Empire rose as a formidable new power that redefined the political and spiritual landscape of Persia. Under the command of Shah Ismail I, fractured territories were fiercely unified with the backing of the elite Qizilbash military order, establishing Shia Islam as the bedrock of the state\'s identity. Entering the reign of Shah Abbas the Great, the empire embraced its absolute golden age. The capital was relocated to Isfahan, a city transformed into a global masterpiece of urban planning, adorned with the captivating turquoise domes of the Shah Mosque, and established as the epicenter for international trade, silk carpets, and Persian miniature arts. Yet, even the most exquisite crown is not immune to twilight. By the mid-18th century, a maelstrom of internal strife weakened the state, inviting brutal invasions by Afghan and Ottoman forces. The fall of the Safavid throne in 1736 may have ended a dynasty, but it left behind a monumental legacy of cultural identity and artistic masterpieces that endure across the ages.',
