                        textEn: 'Following the historical footsteps of Barus, the northern coast of Sumatra bore witness to the birth of the Jeumpa Kingdom — the first and oldest Islamic political entity in the Nusantara. Standing gracefully in the lush hills between the Peudada River and Pante Krueng Peusangan, Bireuen, Aceh, this region pulsed as a strategic trading port that wove together the convergence of Arab, Persian, and Chinese merchants. This civilizational epic began in the 8th century CE, when Syahriansyah Salman Al-Parsi, a nobleman of Arab-Persian descent, tied his fate to Mayang Seludang, the daughter of the local ruler. This sacred marriage became a monumental turning point for a region that initially held tightly to local beliefs. Upon ascending to leadership, Syahriansyah gently introduced and sowed the values of Islamic teachings. Between the years 770 and 777 CE, Jeumpa fully transformed into an Islamic-styled kingdom, establishing itself as the earliest pillar and epicenter radiating the light of faith across the archipelago. Yet, as the wheel of history turns, this era of hegemony gradually dimmed approaching 880 CE, eventually replaced by the rising power of the Peureulak Sultanate. Even though its throne faded into the shadows of time, Jeumpa refuses to vanish from memory, bequeathing a timeless spiritual foundation and carving its name eternally as the grand pioneer of Islamic civilization in the land of Aceh.',
