                        textEn: "On the strategic shores of the Malacca Strait, the Peureulak Sultanate pulsed as a vital artery of global commerce and an early epicenter of Islam in the Nusantara. World-renowned for its premium perlak shipbuilding timber, the port became a grand convergence point for fleets from Arabia, India, and China. Through peaceful trade and the profound assimilation by scholars like Sheikh Abdullah bin Arif, Islam took firm root, leading to the sultanate's official establishment in 840 CE under Sultan Alaidin Sayyid Maulana Abdul Aziz Syah. Despite being tested by internal conflicts and 10th-century wars against the Sriwijaya Empire, Peureulak reached its intellectual zenith in the 13th century as a premier center for Islamic education. Its grandeur, witnessed firsthand by Marco Polo in 1291 CE, ultimately merged with the Samudera Pasai Sultanate through a royal marriage in 1292, laying the eternal foundation stone for the glorious Islamic civilization across the entire archipelago.",
